<h1>From Charles Smith</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dr Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Fort Loudoun Sepr 18 1758</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Your Letter of the 12th Came safe to Hand. According to Your Desire I Immediately sent the Inclosd Down to hardwick.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>I have Imployd a man of Skill to Assist me in Doing the stone worke of the Bastiane which I am affraid it will be a very Troublesom undertakeing as all the old work must be Taken away &amp; new Pillars raisd, you may be sure there is no Soldier here fit for Duty but what is kept constantly at Labour to keep things in Repair.</p>
<p>Now I have wrote to Saml Givings for the Brand &amp; markes of your Black Mare, &amp; then will take Every Method, I Can to get them. I will Advertise them at Every Publick Place, I Can think off.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>The Horse that Burres rode Down is a Light bay about 14 Hands high, favours a horse I have seen you have no brands, only some white hairs Groing on the top of his Neck the Reason of my Stoping himBurres first told me he was Yours, &amp; you Lent him &amp; afterwards Offered him for Sale, hardwick says he Does not know him to be Yours.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>Your Peter has mended very Little since my Last but is able to do some small Trifles in the Shop.</p>
<p>Hardwick has been a Speakeing to me, that he is Realy Intended to Leave Your Imploy as soon as his time is up. Your Waggoner John behaves Extreamly ill, &amp; Consults his own Interest more then Yours.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0004-ptr">4</a></p>
<p>I have got one of your waggons &amp; Neagra addam to Drive for the Publick, &amp; some Imploy I get about Town that is when it can be spard from the Quarter.</p>
<p>As there is many of the officers Looses men by Desertion, Writes to me Desireing, to Advertise them at 2 Reward, I must Certainly Pay the Money when any Soldier Deliverd to me as a Deserter, &amp; they haveing my Advartisement I take a Receipt for the money I advance that I know, but I Should be vastly oblige to you for your advice, in Leting me know, how I Shall be Repaid, as I have sent advertisemts to all Parts of Virga &amp; some to North Carrolina this I look upon to be my Duty when Required for the good of the publick. I Receivd one of the 1st Virga Regt Deserter from Lieut. Kings Commd of the 10th &amp; 3 belonging
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-06-02-pb-0026">[26]</span>
to the North Carolinia Detachment (that Scoundral) Hansley after being pardind Deserted Last night<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0005" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> as I am in a Hurry, of writeing an answer to the Governours Letter I hope you will Excuse my not sending You the weekly Returnes, but there is nothing happened Extraordinary Since my Last only Receivd 4 Deserters, hansley Deserted &amp; one Dead of the old Regt.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0006" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0006-ptr">6</a></p>
<p>it makes our Duty Very hard to keep so many Prisoners I think it would be very Advisable to Clap them to Labour as there is a Nessaity at this time.</p>
<p>Mr Rutherford will have about, 30, or 40, Waggons Ready to start from this Place of the 22d Loaded with Fluor &amp; Forrage, but is at a Loss what to do for a Guard of Men if you think Proper I can spare the 20 Raingers as far as pierce halls, but must have your advice in this case.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0007" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0007-ptr">7</a></p>
<p>I have Inclosd my Pay Role for the Month of Augt for Subsistance &amp; Workeing Pay, Concludeing my self as Super Intendent of the Publick work<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0008" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0008-ptr">8</a>there is David Davis of Colo: Stephens Compy Richd Trotter of Capt. Woodwards Compy has not Receivd any Subsistance for 6 Months, Past, I Did not know if it was Advisable or not to Put them in my Pay Roles or not, but have at the bottoms without you spake to Mr Boyd Concerning the men that is Joind me sence your Departure he will not send whats Due to them.</p>
<p>As Mr Redeford has Aplied to me for a Guard to go up with the Waggons as Lord Farfax denys sending One of the Militia &amp; the teams Lying here at Expence Loaded with forrage I thought it Nessasary for the good of the Service to Send Express to You to know if I am to Send the 20 Rangers that is under my Command as far as Piercealls Or not I beg for an imediate Answer as the Waggons Lyes here upon Expence.</p>
<p>The Express from Alexandria has not returnd Yet<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0009" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0009-ptr">9</a> I am Dear Sir Your Very Humbe Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Chs Smith</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>GWs letter of 12 Sept. to Smith is missing as is the letter he enclosed to Christopher Hardwick.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>For other references to the black mare that GW bought from Edward Snickers, see especially <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0364&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0364-fn-0003#GEWN-02-05-02-0364-fn-0003" class="document">Christopher Hardwick to GW, 3 Sept. 1758, n.3</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>Thomas Burris brought GWs letters down from Fort Cumberland to Winchester and Alexandria in late August. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0354&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0354-fn-0005#GEWN-02-05-02-0354-fn-0005" class="document">George William Fairfax to GW,
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-06-02-pb-0027">[27]</span>
1 Sept. 1758 (first letter), n.5.</a> Smith took this horse, the Light bay, from Burris on Burriss return from Alexandria to Winchester on his way back to Fort Cumberland (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0002&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0007#GEWN-02-06-02-0002-fn-0007" class="document">Smith to GW, 7 Sept. 1758, n.7</a>). This was the same villain Burrass who in 1756 sold or swapped one of GWs horses (<a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0345" class="document">GW to Adam Stephen, 6 Sept. 1756</a>). For Burriss earlier career in GWs regiment, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-02-02-0055&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-02-02-0055-fn-0002#GEWN-02-02-02-0055-fn-0002" class="document">Adam Stephen to GW, 25 Sept. 1755, n.2</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>Smith seems to have changed his opinion of the wagoner John Adams by the time he wrote to GW on 16 Nov. about Hardwicks mistreatment of John.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0005">5</a>
   
   <p>The law dealing with desertion (7 <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William Waller Hening, ed. &lt;i&gt;The Statutes at Large; Being a Collection of All the Laws of Virginia, from the First Session of the Legislature, in the Year 1619&lt;/i&gt;. 13 vols. 181923. Reprint. Charlottesville, Va., 1969. ]">Hening</span> 8792) provided that a justice of the peace should issue to anyone who took up a deserter a certificate entitling him to collect 200 pounds of tobacco from the public. For earlier references to the deserter Christopher Hensley, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0344&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0344-fn-0002#GEWN-02-05-02-0344-fn-0002" class="document">Smith to GW, 27 Aug., n.2.</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0002" class="document">7 September</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>The most recent return of the garrison at Fort Loudoun that has been found is dated 4 Aug. 1758. For this, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0344&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0344-fn-0001#GEWN-02-05-02-0344-fn-0001" class="document">Smith to GW, 27 Aug., n.1</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>After getting GWs response to this letter, Smith sent twenty rangers and twenty Culpeper County militiamen to escort Commissary Thomas Rutherfords wagon train of provisions to Job Pearsals (pierce halls) and on up to Fort Cumberland. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0059" class="document">Smith to GW, 12 Oct. 1758</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0008">8</a>

   <p>The payroll for the men working on Fort Loudoun at Winchester under Lieutenant Smiths supervision has not been found.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0009-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0025-fn-0009">9</a>

   <p>Presumably the Express to whom he is referring is the same (unidentified) man who took <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0012" class="document">GWs letters of 12 Sept. to George William Fairfax</a> and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0013" class="document">to his wife Sarah Cary Fairfax</a>.</p>
                      
</div>
